# DEBUG decisions log — hit-count undercount under concurrency
# Mode: DEBUG (read-only Plan Mode). Reproduce-first. No source edits; STOP before fix.

== 2026-05-29 — OBSERVATION (precise, pre-interpretation) ==
- Symptom: GET /api/stats/:code reports hits < actual redirects, ONLY under many
  concurrent requests to the SAME high-traffic code. Low-traffic codes accurate.
  Single request always counted. Full suite green (51/51) so CI misses it.
- Repro (test/hit-concurrency.test.js): N=200 concurrent store.incrementHit() on
  one code via Promise.all, then assert stats.hits === N.
  RESULT: expected 200, actual 1, lost 199. Deterministic (fails every run).
- Full suite with repro added: 51 pass + 1 fail (only the new repro fails).

== FRAME ==
Why does incrementHit lose updates under concurrency while create() (also
concurrency-tested at 50x) does not?

== LOCALIZE ==
- Single commit in repo (c3d74f6). `git status` shows a PRE-EXISTING uncommitted
  modification: `M src/store.js` (NOT made by this investigation).
- `git diff src/store.js` shows the introducing change at incrementHit (lines ~48-56):
  the record READ was hoisted OUT of the enqueue() lock under a "perf" comment.
    BEFORE (committed, correct): get(code) + hits+1 INSIDE enqueue (atomic RMW).
    AFTER  (working tree, buggy): `const existing = links.get(code)` read OUTSIDE
    enqueue; only the write runs inside the lock.

== HYPOTHESES (competing) ==
H1 [LEAD] Lost-update race: read-outside-lock in incrementHit.
   Each concurrent call captures `existing` (hits=N) BEFORE any peer commits, then
   inside the lock writes `existing.hits + 1`. All callers share the same stale
   snapshot, so commits overwrite each other -> final = (last writer's snapshot)+1.
   FOR:
   - Code path: read at src/store.js:54 is outside enqueue (line 55); the mutex
     only serializes the WRITE, not the read-modify-write as a unit.
   - create() reads freshCode() INSIDE enqueue (src/store.js:39-44) -> its 50x
     concurrency test passes; structural contrast matches "create ok, hit broken".
   - Repro: 200 concurrent -> actual 1 (all share hits=0 snapshot -> all write 1).
   - Discriminating probe: git stash the diff, run repro on COMMITTED store ->
     200/200, 0 lost. Restore -> 1/200. Bug lives entirely in this diff. CONFIRMED.
   AGAINST: none found.

H2 Persistence/atomic-write timing (torn writes, .tmp/rename) drops counts.
   FOR: writes are async (persist() temp+rename) so a crash window could lose data.
   AGAINST: store.test.js "50 concurrent creates" verifies all 50 persisted +
     valid JSON + no leftover .tmp -> the temp+rename path is sound under
     concurrency. Repro never crashes; undercount is in-memory (stats() reads the
     Map directly, src/store.js:68-71, not disk). REJECTED.

H3 Counter type / serialization (hits not numeric, JSON coercion).
   FOR: records are frozen and JSON-serialized.
   AGAINST: round-trip test asserts hits===1 numeric; reload test reads hits===1
     from disk. Type is fine; loss is concurrency-only. REJECTED.

H4 Stats reads stale data (reader-side, not writer-side).
   FOR: symptom phrased around the stats endpoint.
   AGAINST: stats() returns links.get() from the in-memory source of truth; the
     repro reads stats AFTER all increments settle (Promise.all resolved) and still
     sees 1. The loss is in the WRITE path, not the read. REJECTED.

== LENSES ==
- Systems: the enqueue() mutex is a write-serialization queue but the critical
  section was shrunk to exclude the read. A correct mutex must wrap the whole
  read-modify-write; here R is outside, M+W inside -> classic check-then-act race.
- Premortem: could it be event-loop scheduling making it only "sometimes" lose?
  No — because all reads happen synchronously before any microtask commits, the
  loss is near-total (199/200), not flaky. Matches "intermittent in prod" because
  prod requests arrive spread over time; only those overlapping within one
  read-before-commit window collide. Low-traffic = no overlap = accurate. Fits.
- Science: control = committed store.js (passes 200/200); variable = the 5-line
  diff; outcome flips to 1/200. Single-variable causal proof.

== REBUTTAL ROUND ==
- Best challenge to H1: "Node is single-threaded; how can there be a race?"
- Rebuttal: cooperative concurrency still races across await points. incrementHit
  reads `existing` synchronously, then `enqueue` defers the write to a later
  microtask (writeChain.then). All 200 synchronous reads run before any deferred
  write, so every write is computed from the same pre-commit snapshot. The mutex
  prevents interleaved WRITES, not stale READS. H1 stands.

== CONVERGENCE / SEPARATION ==
- H1 is the sole surviving mechanism. H2/H3/H4 are genuinely distinct and each
  refuted by an existing green test or by the in-memory nature of the loss. No
  fake convergence.

== ROOT CAUSE (CONFIRMED) ==
src/store.js incrementHit (working-tree version), lines ~51-61:
  const existing = links.get(code);      // <- READ outside the lock (line 54)
  if (!existing) return null;
  return enqueue(async () => {
    const updated = Object.freeze({ ...existing, hits: existing.hits + 1 }); // stale base
    links.set(code, updated);
    await persist();
  });
Interleaving (N=2): both call incrementHit; both synchronously read existing.hits=5
before either's enqueued write runs; writer A commits hits=6; writer B commits
hits=6 (from its own stale snapshot of 5). One increment lost. At N=200 all share
hits=0 -> final=1.

== MINIMAL FIX (PROPOSED, NOT APPLIED) ==
Move the read back INSIDE enqueue so the read-modify-write is one atomic critical
section (revert to committed behavior). I.e. restore:
  async function incrementHit(code) {
    ensureInit();
    return enqueue(async () => {
      const existing = links.get(code);
      if (!existing) return null;
      const updated = Object.freeze({ ...existing, hits: existing.hits + 1 });
      links.set(code, updated);
      await persist();
      return updated;
    });
  }
Equivalent: `git checkout -- src/store.js` reverts the offending uncommitted diff.
The "perf" comment (lines 48-50) should be removed with it.

== REGRESSION GUARD ==
Keep test/hit-concurrency.test.js (200x concurrent incrementHit === 200). It fails
on the buggy version and passes on the committed/fixed version — closes the CI gap.

